. Actually the code doesn't make sense. I think you test with FF. You have to distinguish between Chrome, Firefox and IE < 10. 
In case you load the forms polyfill IE will behave exactly the same like FF without any polyfill. (pattern seems to work).
In case you load the forms and the forms-ext polyfill IE will work exactly the same like chrome. But FF will behave a little bit different here. The reason is simple: FF does implement pattern, but not type=number. (And I do not check wether pattern attribute is used correctly in FF).
By definition pattern does not apply to type="number", your pattern is a spec violation and isn't taken into account by IE (if fully polyfilled) or in Chrome (fully capable). Additionally you can simply skip $ and ^ those are automatically added.
I think you want to have something like this:
<input type="number" step="0.01" />
or
<input type="number" step="0.01" min="0" />
Does this help? Or what do you want to achieve exactly?
