. This is because webshim's UI components also need to know, if you change something, this is done by simply using jQuery's prop method. But KnockoutJS, doesn't use jQuery:
If you change Knockout code, it would work:
Old version:
ko.bindingHandlers['enable'] = {
    'update': function (element, valueAccessor) {
        var value = ko.utils.unwrapObservable(valueAccessor());
        if (value && element.disabled)
            element.removeAttribute("disabled");
        else if ((!value) && (!element.disabled))
            element.disabled = true;
    }
};
New version:
ko.bindingHandlers['enable'] = {
    'update': function (element, valueAccessor) {
        var value = ko.utils.unwrapObservable(valueAccessor());
        if (value && element.disabled)
            $.prop(element, 'disabled', false);
        else if ((!value) && (!element.disabled))
            $.prop(element, 'disabled', true);
    }
};
I don't develop with Knockout, but if they provide some Hooks for thier bindings, you can hook into and simply write somecode like this:
//set disabled property to it's current disabled state using $.prop to update UI component
$.prop(element, 'disabled', element.disabled );
